  "text": "## TypeScript Module Resolution System Analysis\n\n### Overview\nThe TypeScript module resolution system is implemented entirely in `src/compiler/moduleNameResolver.ts` (3417 lines). It implements five resolution strategies that can be selected via compiler options: Classic, Node10 (legacy Node), Node16, NodeNext, and Bundler.\n\n### Main Entry Point and Strategy Dispatch\n**`resolveModuleName` (line 1401)** is the main entry point that handles:\n- Cache lookup and storage\n- Module resolution kind selection (lines 1421-1427)\n- Strategy dispatch via switch statement (lines 1434-1452)\n- Tracing and diagnostics output (lines 1463-1475)\n\nThe strategy dispatch routes to:\n- `node16ModuleNameResolver` (line 1436) - Node16 strategy\n- `nodeNextModuleNameResolver` (line 1439) - NodeNext strategy\n- `nodeModuleNameResolver` (line 1442) - Node10 strategy\n- `classicNameResolver` (line 1445) - Classic strategy\n- `bundlerModuleNameResolver` (line 1448) - Bundler strategy\n\n### Node16 and NodeNext Strategies\n**`node16ModuleNameResolver` (line 1704)** and **`nodeNextModuleNameResolver` (line 1717)** are thin wrappers that delegate to **`nodeNextModuleNameResolverWorker` (line 1730)** with different feature flags:\n- Node16 uses `NodeResolutionFeatures.Node16Default`\n- NodeNext uses `NodeResolutionFeatures.NodeNextDefault`\n\nThey handle extension selection (TypeScript, JavaScript, Declaration, optional JSON) and pass control to the core worker.\n\n### Core Node-like Resolution: nodeModuleNameResolverWorker\n**`nodeModuleNameResolverWorker` (line 1795)** is the universal worker for all node-like strategies (Node10, Node16, NodeNext, Bundler). It:\n- Initializes the ModuleResolutionState object with conditions, features, and diagnostic reporter (lines 1820-1834)\n- Handles resolution mode (ESM vs CJS) (lines 1812-1817)\n- Provides fallback diagnostics for conflicting strategy results (lines 1851-1891)\n- Delegates to internal `tryResolve` function that handles the actual resolution logic\n\n### Package.json Exports Field Resolution\n**`getPackageJsonInfo` (line 2440)** reads and caches package.json files:\n- Returns early if not found in cache\n- Reads file contents via `readJson`\n- Caches results in `packageJsonInfoCache`\n- Tracks failed lookup locations for invalidation\n\n**`loadModuleFromExports` (line 2613)** implements package.json exports resolution:\n- Checks if exports field exists\n- Handles main export (exports = \"./file\") at subpath \".\"\n- Routes named exports to `loadModuleFromExportsOrImports`\n\n**`loadModuleFromImports` (line 2650)** implements package.json imports resolution:\n- Validates import specifier format (#-prefixed)\n- Finds containing package scope\n- Routes to `loadModuleFromExportsOrImports`\n\n**`loadModuleFromExportsOrImports` (line 2702)** performs pattern matching:\n- First checks for exact matches via `hasProperty`\n- Then checks pattern matches via sorted `expandingKeys`\n- Supports pattern trailers (lines 2711-2715)\n- Supports wildcard patterns ending with * (lines 2717-2720)\n- Supports directory patterns ending with / (lines 2722-2726)\n- Uses **`comparePatternKeys` (line 2688)** for longest-match ordering per Node.js spec\n\n### Classic Strategy\n**`classicNameResolver` (line 3250)** implements TypeScript's original resolution:\n- Creates ModuleResolutionState with no NodeResolutionFeatures\n- Tries two passes: TypeScript/Declaration first, then JavaScript/JSON\n- For relative imports: resolves candidate file directly\n- For non-relative imports: climbs ancestor directories (with cache lookups)\n- Falls back to @types directories and typeRoots\n- No package.json exports/imports support\n\n### Path Mapping Resolution\n**`tryLoadModuleUsingPaths` (line 3158)** handles baseUrl and paths compiler options:\n- Uses **`matchPatternOrExact`** (imported from utilities) to find matching pattern\n- Iterates through path substitutions for the matched pattern\n- Performs star substitution via `replaceFirstStar`\n- Normalizes paths via `combinePaths`\n- Supports explicit extensions in path patterns (lines 3174-3180)\n\nPath matching is used by both Classic and Node-like strategies via `tryLoadModuleUsingOptionalResolutionSettings` (line 1550).\n\n### Supporting Module Loading Functions\n**`loadNodeModuleFromDirectory` (line 2209)** loads modules from directories:\n- Calls `getPackageJsonInfo` to retrieve package.json\n- Delegates to `loadNodeModuleFromDirectoryWorker`\n\n**`loadNodeModuleFromDirectoryWorker` (line 2484)** handles package.json field reading:\n- Reads package.json fields (main, types, typesVersions)\n- Supports versionPaths via pattern matching\n- Falls back to index file resolution (except in ESM mode)\n\n**`loadModuleFromFile` (line 2064)** loads from file paths:\n- Attempts implicit extension replacement (.js → .ts)\n- Falls back to explicit file checking\n- Handles TypeScript, JavaScript, Declaration, and JSON extensions\n\n### Tracing and Diagnostics\n**`trace` (line 115)** outputs resolution diagnostics:\n- Takes `DiagnosticMessage` and format args\n- Calls `host.trace()` with formatted output\n- Used throughout for resolution step logging\n\n**`isTraceEnabled` (line 120)** checks if tracing is active:\n- Checks `compilerOptions.traceResolution` flag\n- Verifies `host.trace` function exists\n\n**Diagnostic reporting** is integrated via:\n- `reportDiagnostic` callback in ModuleResolutionState (line 326)\n- Collects diagnostics in array during resolution (line 1819)\n- Returned in final result (line 1899)\n- Examples: conflicting resolution strategies, missing exports, pattern mismatches\n\n### Resolution Strategy Features\nAll strategies support optional augmentation via:\n- **baseUrl**: Controls non-relative module resolution base directory\n- **paths**: Maps module names to alternate locations\n- **rootDirs**: Maps virtual project structure to runtime structure\n- **traceResolution**: Enables diagnostic output\n- **typeRoots**: Specifies @types search locations (TypeScript only)\n- **typesVersions**: Version-specific type definitions in package.json\n\nNode16/NodeNext additionally support:\n- **exports/imports**: Package.json conditional and pattern exports\n- **conditions**: Export conditions (import/require, browser/node, types, etc.)\n- **package.json type**: Determines ESM vs CommonJS mode\n\n### Key Interfaces and Enums\n- **ModuleResolutionState**: Central context object carrying options, host, cache, features, conditions, diagnostics\n- **NodeResolutionFeatures**: Flags for enabling specific Node.js resolution features\n- **Extensions**: Enum for file type filtering (TypeScript, JavaScript, Declaration, JSON)\n- **Resolved**: Result interface with path, extension, packageId, originalPath\n- **PathAndExtension**: Intermediate result before packageId addition\n- **ModuleResolutionCache**: Caches results per directory and non-relative name\n- **PackageJsonInfoCache**: Caches parsed package.json contents\n\n### File Organization\nAll module resolution logic is contained in the single file `src/compiler/moduleNameResolver.ts`, making it a self-contained, cohesive subsystem for handling all TypeScript module resolution strategies from initial dispatch through package.json parsing and pattern matching to final file location determination."
